The basic structure of a jQuery Mobile page follows a clear layout pattern composed of a page container and optional header, content, and footer sections. Each section is defined using `data-role` attributes. jQuery Mobile enhances these elements automatically to create a mobile-optimized interface. The essential requirement is to include the correct meta viewport tag and the jQuery + jQuery Mobile CDN files in the `<head>` of the HTML document. After that, each page is wrapped in a `<div data-role="page">` container that includes the page header, main content, and footer. This structure forms the foundation for building single-page or multi-page mobile applications within one HTML file.

**Basic Structure of jQuery Mobile Page**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
  <!-- jQuery Mobile CDN Files -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.css">
  <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.11.1.min.js"></script>
  <script src="https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.js"></script>
</head>

<body>
  <div data-role="page" id="home">

    <div data-role="header">
      <h1>Header</h1>
    </div>

    <div data-role="content">
      <p>Welcome to jQuery Mobile Page!</p>
    </div>

    <div data-role="footer">
      <h4>Footer</h4>
    </div>

  </div>
</body>
</html>
```

This structure represents the minimal and complete format for a jQuery Mobile page.

**CDN Files Used with jQuery Mobile**

1. **jQuery Mobile CSS File**
   `https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.css`

2. **jQuery Library File**
   `https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.11.1.min.js`

3. **jQuery Mobile JavaScript File**
   `https://code.jquery.com/mobile/1.4.5/jquery.mobile-1.4.5.min.js`

These three CDN files are mandatory for enabling jQuery Mobileâ€™s UI components, themes, widgets, touch interactions, and navigation system.
